    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:a58d0820-404e-4055-9412-3408c73684a5",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 51-year-old man who looks tired but not acutely ill, sitting carefully in the exam chair and shifting his shoulders and thighs as if trying to find a comfortable position. He describes a dull, aching soreness in multiple muscle groups that has been building over the last 10 days, most noticeably in his neck, upper back, lower back, and both thighs. He is able to walk and speak normally, but he moves a little more slowly than usual and occasionally rubs his forearms and calves. He denies focal weakness, chest pain, shortness of breath, or dark urine, but says the muscle pain is interfering with sleep and daily chores.\n\n{patientName} works as a warehouse supervisor, a job that keeps him on his feet for long hours and sometimes requires helping with lifting when staffing is short. Outside work he enjoys weekend fishing, watching football with friends, and doing small home improvement projects in his garage. Over the last two weeks he helped his brother move furniture and has continued working full shifts, which he believes may have worsened the pain. He usually tries to \"push through\" discomfort rather than seek care early.\n\nHe lives with his wife, and his two adult children visit often. His family describes him as dependable and active, though lately he has become more irritable from poor sleep and persistent soreness. He drinks coffee heavily during workdays, has 1-2 beers on some weekends, and does not use illicit drugs. He is a former smoker who quit years ago. His diet is variable, often relying on quick convenience meals during busy shifts, and he admits he does not stretch regularly or stay well hydrated at work.\n\nIn the clinic he appears mildly uncomfortable but engaged and cooperative. There is diffuse muscle tenderness on palpation without visible swelling, rash, or joint deformity. He worries that the pain might represent \"something serious,\" but is reassured by the absence of red-flag symptoms and the pattern of generalized muscle aching after overuse. He is hoping for relief that will allow him to sleep better and keep working."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:c0c8345e-3648-4ded-9781-b4c81ebfc2f4",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of intermittent mechanical low back pain and mild essential hypertension managed conservatively. He has no known history of autoimmune disease, chronic kidney disease, or statin use. He reports no recent febrile illness, no recent travel, and no new prescription medications. He was evaluated in urgent care once 3 years ago for a lumbar strain after lifting at work, which improved with rest and non-opioid analgesics.\n\nOver the past 10 days, {patientName} developed progressive generalized muscle aching after a period of unusually heavy physical activity, including overtime shifts and helping move furniture. The pain is worse in the evening and after exertion, with morning stiffness lasting about 15 minutes. He denies focal numbness, true weakness, bowel or bladder changes, rash, joint redness, or trauma. He has been taking occasional over-the-counter acetaminophen with partial relief. Sleep has been reduced because turning in bed aggravates the muscle soreness.\n\nLifestyle factors relevant to his presentation include physically demanding work, inconsistent hydration, poor stretching habits, and fragmented sleep. He quit smoking 12 years ago after a 15-pack-year history. He drinks alcohol socially in small amounts and does not use recreational drugs."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
